ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of relative amount of a substance that combines with or displaces 8.0 grams of oxygen or 1.008 gram of hydrogen. The unit is usually expressed in grams and is equal to the amount of substance that gains or loses one mole of electrons in a redox reaction, or to the amount of substances that releases or accepts one mole of hydrogen ions in a neutralization reaction; or to the amount of electrolyte that carries one mole of positive or negative charge. This is a large unit and measurements are more often done in its derivatives, e.g. in milliequivalents.

Concepts.definition: A unit of relative amount of a substance that combines with or displaces 8.0 grams of oxygen or 1.008 gram of hydrogen. The unit is usually expressed in grams and is equal to the amount of substance that gains or loses one mole of electrons in a redox reaction, or to the amount of substances that releases or accepts one mole of hydrogen ions in a neutralization reaction; or to the amount of electrolyte that carries one mole of positive or negative charge. ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A metric unit of areal density defined as a spread rate at which one gram of a substance is spread over the area of one square meter. ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The SI derived unit of absorbed radiation dose. One gray is equal to an absorbed dose of one joule per kilogram of matter; one gray equals 100 rads. Concepts.definition: A SI derived unit of absorbed radiation dose. One gray is equal to an absorbed dose of one joule per kilogram of matter, or to 100 rads.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of a mass fraction expressed as a number of micrograms of substance per kilogram of mixture. The unit is also used as a dose calculation unit.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A metric unit of areal density equal to approximately 2.94935E-8 ounce per square yard. Also used as a dose calculation unit.

Concepts.definition: A metric unit of areal density equal to approximately 2.94935E-8 ounce per square yard. Also used as a dose calculation unit.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A metric unit of volume equal to one millionth of a liter or one one thousandth of a milliliter.

Concepts.definition: A unit of volume accepted for use with the SI and equal to one millionth of a liter (10E-6 liter).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of amount of substance equal to a millionth of a mole.

Concepts.definition: A unit of amount of substance equal to a millionth of a mole.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of volume used in pharmacy and equal to 0.05 milliliter (20 drops/ml).

Concepts.definition: A unit of volume used in pharmacy and equal to 0.05 milliliter (20 drops/ml).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The US unit of liquid volume legally defined as 3785.411784 milliliters (3.785 411 784 liters), or 231 cubic inches. The US gallon holds 4 liquid quarts; the gallon of water gallon weighs approximately 8.33 pounds.

Concepts.definition: The US unit of liquid volume legally defined as 3785.411784 milliliters (3.785 411 784 liters), or 231 cubic inches. The US gallon holds 4 liquid quarts; the gallon of water gallon weighs approximately 8.33 pounds.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The unitage assigned by the WHO to International Biological Standards - substances, classed as biological according to the criteria provided by WHO Expert Committee on Biological Standardization (e.g. hormones, enzymes, and vaccines), to enable the results of biological and immunological assay procedures to be expressed in the same way throughout the world. The definition of an international unit is generally arbitrary and technical, and has to be officially approved by the International Conference for Unification of Formulae.

Concepts.definition: The unitage assigned by the WHO to International Biological Standards - substances, classed as biological according to the criteria provided by WHO Expert Committee on Biological Standardization (e.g. hormones, enzymes, and vaccines), to enable the results of biological and immunological assay procedures to be expressed in the same way throughout the world. The definition of an international unit is generally arbitrary and technical, and has to be officially approved by the International Conference for Unification of Formulae.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An arbitrary unit of substance content expressed in international units of biological activity per one kilogram of mass of the system. It is also used as a dose calculation unit expressed in international units of biological activity per one kilogram of body mass.

Concepts.definition: A unit of measure of a quantity of substance per unit mass, expressed as the quantity of substance in International Units, divided by the mass of the substance in kilograms. It is also used as a dose calculation unit expressed in International Units of biological activity per one kilogram of body mass.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one international unit per one liter of the system volume.

Concepts.definition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one international unit per one liter of the system volume.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one international unit per one milligram of substance.

Concepts.definition: A unit of measure of quantity of substance per unit mass, expressed in terms of International Units per milligram. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: International Unit per Milligram of Alpha-Tocopherol

ValueMeaning.preferredName: International Unit per Milligram of Alpha-Tocopherol
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one international unit of alpha-Tocopherol per one milligram of preparation.

Concepts.longName: International Unit per Milligram of Alpha-Tocopherol
Concepts.definition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one international unit of alpha-Tocopherol per one milligram of preparation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An arbitrary unit of measurement of the specific biological activity of vitamin A, defined by the International Conference for Unification of Formula as equal approximately to 0.30 micrograms of all-trans retinol or to 0.60 micrograms of the provitamin A, all-trans-beta-carotene.

Concepts.definition: An arbitrary unit of measurement of the specific biological activity of vitamin A, defined by the International Conference for Unification of Formula as equal approximately to 0.30 micrograms of all-trans retinol or to 0.60 micrograms of the provitamin A, all-trans-beta-carotene.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The traditional unit of mass. The avoirdupois ounce is equal to 1/16 pound, or 28.3495 grams, or 0.911 457 troy ounce.

Concepts.definition: The traditional unit of mass. The avoirdupois ounce is equal to 1/16 pound, or 28.349 5 grams, or 0.911 457 troy ounce.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A traditional unit of pressure equivalent to 6.894757 kilopascals, or 703.0696 kilograms per square meter, or 51.71507 millimeters of mercury.

Concepts.definition: A traditional unit of pressure equivalent to 6.894757 kilopascals, or 703.0696 kilograms per square meter, or 51.71507 millimeters of mercury.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of radiation absorbed dose equal to the amount of energy from any type of ionizing radiation (e.g., alpha, beta, gamma, neutrons, etc.) deposited in any medium (e.g., water, tissue, air). A dose of one rad means the absorption of 100 ergs (a small but measurable amount of energy) per gram of absorbing tissue (100 rad = 1 gray). (NRC)

Concepts.definition: A unit of radiation absorbed dose equal to the amount of energy from any type of ionizing radiation (e.g., alpha, beta, gamma, neutrons, etc.) deposited in any medium (e.g., water, tissue, air). A dose of one rad means the absorption of 100 ergs per gram of absorbing tissue (100 rad = 1 gray). (The U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission, NRC).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of volume informally used in pharmacy. Under the metric system the tablespoon has been standardized at 15 milliliters in the US, Britain, Canada, and New Zealand, and at 20 milliliters in Australia and some European countries.

Concepts.definition: A unit of volume informally used in pharmacy. Under the metric system the tablespoon has been standardized at 15 milliliters in the US, Britain, Canada, and New Zealand, and at 20 milliliters in Australia and some European countries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of volume used in pharmacy and equal to 5 milliliters.

Concepts.definition: A unit of volume used in pharmacy and equal to 5 milliliters.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing measurement based on the application unit.

Concepts.definition: A dosing measurement based on the application unit.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The area between the x-axis and the curve given by the integrand. It is equal to the definite integral of a function. In the field of pharmacokinetics, the area under the curve (AUC) is the area under the curve in a plot of concentration of a drug in plasma against time. AUC is usually given for the time interval zero to infinity, and other time intervals are indicated.

Concepts.definition: The area between the x-axis and the curve given by the integrand. It is equal to the definite integral of a function. In the field of pharmacokinetics, the area under the curve (AUC) is the area under the curve in a plot of concentration of a drug in plasma against time. AUC is usually given for the time interval zero to infinity, and other time intervals are indicated.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit that contains medicinal substance(s) in the form of a receptacle with a narrow neck designed to accept a specific closure.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a bottle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a caplet.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a caplet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a capsule.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a capsule.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The smallest units of living structure capable of independent existence, composed of a membrane-enclosed mass of protoplasm and containing a nucleus or nucleoid. Cells are highly variable and specialized in both structure and function, though all must at some stage replicate proteins and nucleic acids, utilize energy, and reproduce themselves.

Concepts.definition: The smallest units of living structure capable of independent existence, composed of a membrane-enclosed mass of protoplasm and containing a nucleus or nucleoid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A period of protocol-prescribed activity or intervention.

Concepts.definition: Passage through time; duration; a systematic or/and orderly succession; a sequence, e.g. course of treatment; a mode of action or behavior; natural development, typical manner of proceeding.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An event or sequence of events that constitute round or succession of observable phenomena, recurring usually at regular or approximately regular time intervals and in the same sequence.

Concepts.definition: An event or sequence of events that constitute a round or succession of observable phenomena, recurring usually at regular or approximately regular time intervals and in the same sequence.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The amount of medicine taken, or radiation given, at one time.

Concepts.definition: A quantity of an agent (such as substance or energy) administered, taken, or absorbed at one time.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of the medicinal substance(s) delivered via the respiratory tract by one oral or nasal inhalation in the form of a gas, aerosol, mist, liquid, or fine powder using a nebulizer or an aerosol device, or the force of natural breath.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in an inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a portable container for packaging pharmaceutical dosage forms intended for administration through an intravenous delivery system.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in an intravenous bag.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Measurement; the size or magnitude of something.

Concepts.definition: Annotation used to indicate the size or magnitude of something that was determined by comparison to a standard.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Data from an original source is not present, accessible or ready for use or service.

Concepts.definition: Data from an original source is not present, accessible or ready for use or service.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a single item of a packet dosage form.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a packet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a single item of a patch drug delivery system which often has an adhesive backing that is applied to an external site on the body.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a patch.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measure of viable infectious entities (e.g. viral particles or group of particles) in the specimen or product defined as the smallest quantity that can produce a cytopathic effect in the host cell culture challenged with the defined inoculum, visible under the microscope and/or to the naked eye as a plaque. A number of plaque forming units (PFU) per unit volume is a conventional way to refer the titer of an infective entity in a specimen or preparation.

Concepts.definition: A measure of viable infectious entities (e.g. viral particles or group of particles) in the specimen or product defined as the smallest quantity that can produce a cytopathic effect in the host cell culture challenged with the defined inoculum, visible under the microscope and/or to the naked eye as a plaque. A number of plaque forming units (PFU) per unit volume is a conventional way to refer the titer of an infective entity in a specimen or preparation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to a metered dose of medicinal substance(s) that is delivered in uniform quantity upon each activation of a medical device (e.g. an inhaler), in which the dosage form is contained.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a puff.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An arbitrary unit for measurement of the bioefficacy of ingested provitamin A carotenoids introduced by the U.S. Institute of Medicine (IOM). For a given amount of provitamin A compounds in a mixed diet, IOM estimates that the number of retinol activity e (RAE) is half the number of RE suggested by FAO/WHO. RAE is viewed as an approximate guideline because it was defined on the basis of relatively few studies and limited data on carotenoids bioavailability and bioconversion.

Concepts.definition: An arbitrary unit for measurement of the bioefficacy of ingested provitamin A carotenoids introduced by the U.S. Institute of Medicine (IOM). For a given amount of provitamin A compounds in a mixed diet, IOM estimates that the number of retinol activity e (RAE) is half the number of RE suggested by FAO/WHO. RAE is viewed as an approximate guideline because it was defined on the basis of relatively few studies and limited data on carotenoids bioavailability and bioconversion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An arbitrary unit for measurement of a vitamin A activity of provitamin A carotenoids (such as carotenes, xanthophylls, and compounds that arise from rearrangement of carotene I skeleton) in a mixed diet introduced by FAO/WHO Expert Group in 1967. The concept of the retinol equivalent (RE) is established on the following relationships among food sources of the vitamin A: one microgram of all-trans retinol is equal to one RE, one microgram of beta-carotene is equal to 0.167 RE, and one microgram of other pro-vitamin A carotenoids is equal to 0.084 RE.

Concepts.definition: An arbitrary unit for measurement of a vitamin A activity of provitamin A carotenoids (such as carotenes, xanthophylls, and compounds that arise from rearrangement of carotene I skeleton) in a mixed diet introduced by FAO/WHO Expert Group in 1967. The concept of the retinol equivalent (RE) is established on the following relationships among food sources of the vitamin A: one microgram of all-trans retinol is equal to one RE, one microgram of beta-carotene is equal to 0.167 RE, and one microgram of other pro-vitamin A carotenoids is equal to 0.084 RE.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit in a form of an incapsulated radioactive material that constitutes an implantable pellet designed for brachytherapy administration.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit in a form of an incapsulated radioactive material that constitutes an implantable pellet designed for brachytherapy administration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Time, period, or term devoted to some activity.

Concepts.definition: Time, period, or term devoted to some activity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in the volume of liquid delivered by the single operation of a spray dosage form container.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a spray.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a single item of a suppository dosage form that is designed for introduction into the orifice of the human body and usually melts, softens, or dissolves at body temperature.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a suppository.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a single item of a tablet dosage form comprising of compressed medicinal substance(s) with or without suitable diluents.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a tablet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A quantity of a pathogen required to infect 50% of the tissue cultures inoculated.

Concepts.definition: A potency unit defined as a minimal dose of infectious material at which preparation causes cytopathic effects (changes in the morphology and metabolism of tissue culture cells, indicating cell death, due to suspected infection) in the 50% of the tissue culture-containing flasks inoculated with that dilution of infectious material in the product potency assay or pathogen activity assay.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a single item of a discoid-shaped solid oral dosage form containing the medicinal agent in a suitably flavored base.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a troche.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any division of quantity accepted as a standard of measurement or exchange.

Concepts.definition: A single undivided thing occurring in the composition of something else.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused.

Concepts.definition: Not known, observed, recorded; or reported as unknown by the data contributor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit for virus amount measurement that represents the total number of viral particles (live and dead combined).

Concepts.definition: A unit for virus amount measurement that represents the total number of viral particles (live and dead combined).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin slice of material containing a medicinal agent.

Concepts.definition: A solid composed of a thin slice of material that contain active and/or inert ingredient(s).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit measure of time equal to 60 seconds.

Concepts.definition: A unit measure of time equal to 60 seconds.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: In modern usage, an hour is defined as a unit of time 60 minutes, or 3600 seconds in length. It is approximately 1/24 of a median day.

Concepts.definition: A unit measure of time equal to 3,600 seconds or 60 minutes. It is approximately 1/24 of a median day.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The second is the unit of time, one of the seven base units of the International System of Units (Systeme International d'Unites, SI). The second is the duration of 919 263 177 0 periods of the specified light radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium 133 atom in its ground state at 0 K. According to the convention, 60 seconds constitute one minute; 3,600 seconds constitute one hour. Abbreviation Sec. is acceptable in non-scientific usage only.

Concepts.definition: A unit of time, one of the seven base units of the International System of Units (Systeme International d'Unites, SI). The second is the duration of 919 263 177 0 periods of the specified light radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the caesium 133 atom in its ground state at 0 K. According to the convention, 60 seconds constitute one minute; 3,600 seconds constitute one hour.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A natural number greater than 9 and less than 11 and the quantity that it denotes: the sum of nine and one.: A natural number following 999999 and preceding 100001 and the quantity that it denotes: one thousand thousand.: Various single-celled members of the fungal families, ascomycetes, basidiomycetes and imperfect fungi that tend to be unicellular for the greater part of their life cycle.

Concepts.definition: A natural number greater than 9 and less than 11 and the quantity that it denotes: the sum of nine and one.
A natural number following 999999 and preceding 1000001 and the quantity that it denotes: one thousand thousands.
Various single-celled members of the fungal families, ascomycetes, basidiomycetes and imperfect fungi that tend to be unicellular for the greater part of their life cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose administration rate unit where the amount of product to be delivered or administered is calculated in micrograms as a function of the subject's weight in kilograms and is delivered or administered over the time period of one week.

Concepts.definition: A dose administration rate unit where the amount of product to be delivered or administered is calculated in micrograms as a function of the subject's weight in kilograms and is delivered or administered over the time period of one week.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose administration rate unit equal to the rate at which a gram of a product is delivered or administered over the time period of one week. This is also a unit of mass flow rate equivalent to the rate at which a gram of matter crosses a given surface or is delivered to a given object or space over a period of time equal to one week.

Concepts.definition: A dose administration rate unit equal to the rate at which a gram of a product is delivered or administered over the time period of one week. This is also a unit of mass flow rate equivalent to the rate at which a gram of matter crosses a given surface or is delivered to a given object or space over a period of time equal to one week.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Microgram per Square Meter per Hour

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Microgram per Square Meter per Hour
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose calculation unit expressed in microgram(s) per square meter per period of time equal to sixty minutes.

Concepts.longName: Microgram per Square Meter per Hour
Concepts.definition: A dose calculation unit expressed in microgram(s) per square meter per period of time equal to sixty minutes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose calculation unit expressed in milligram(s) per kilogram per period of time equal to twenty-four hours.

Concepts.definition: A dose calculation unit expressed in milligram(s) per kilogram per period of time equal to twenty-four hours.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A metric mass flow rate unit equal to the rate at which mass of matter of one gram crosses a given surface or/and is transferred over a period of twenty four hours.

Concepts.definition: A metric mass flow rate unit equal to the rate at which mass of matter of one gram crosses a given surface or/and is transferred over a period of twenty four hours.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit for expressing a number as a fraction of hundred (on the basis of a rate or proportion per hundred).

Concepts.definition: A unit for expressing a number as a fraction of hundred (on the basis of a rate or proportion per hundred).

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Milligram per Square Meter per Week

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Milligram per Square Meter per Week
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose calculation unit expressed in milligram(s)per square meter per period of time equal to seven days.

Concepts.longName: Milligram per Square Meter per Week
Concepts.definition: A dose calculation unit expressed in milligram(s) per square meter per period of time equal to seven days.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Milligram per Square Meter per Day

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Milligram per Square Meter per Day
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose calculation unit expressed in milligram(s) per square meter per period of time equal to twenty-four hours.

Concepts.longName: Milligram per Square Meter per Day
Concepts.definition: A dose calculation unit expressed in milligram(s) per square meter per period of time equal to twenty-four hours.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dose calculation unit expressed in microgram(s) per kilogram per period of time equal to twenty-four hours.

Concepts.definition: A dose calculation unit expressed in microgram(s) per kilogram per period of time equal to twenty-four hours.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one millionth of international unit per one milliliter of system volume.

Concepts.definition: Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one millionth of international unit per one milliliter of system volume.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of relative biological effectiveness of protons equivalent to 60 cobalt gamma rays.

Concepts.definition: A unit of relative biological effectiveness of protons equivalent to 60 cobalt gamma rays.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Hundred Million Tissue Culture Infectious Dose 50%

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Hundred Million Tissue Culture Infectious Dose 50%
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of potency equal to one hundred million tissue culture infectious dose 50% units.

Concepts.longName: Hundred Million Tissue Culture Infectious Dose 50%
Concepts.definition: A potency unit equal to the potency at which one dose of preparation contains one million (10^8) 50 percent tissue culture infective doses.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ten Million Tissue Culture Infectious Dose 50%

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ten Million Tissue Culture Infectious Dose 50%
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of potency equal to ten million tissue culture infectious dose 50% units.

Concepts.longName: Ten Million Tissue Culture Infectious Dose 50%
Concepts.definition: A unit of potency equal to ten million tissue culture infectious dose 50% units.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of potency equal to one million tissue culture infectious dose 50% units.

Concepts.definition: A potency unit equal to the potency at which one dose of preparation contains one million (10^6) 50 percent tissue culture infective doses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A unit of biological activity equal to one hundred million international units.

Concepts.definition: A unit of biological activity equal to one hundred million international units.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The metric unit of mass equal to one thousandth of a kilogram. One gram equals approximately 15.432 grains or 0.035 273 966 ounce.: A volume unit equal to one milliliter used as a denominator to build a derived unit expressed as a ratio. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: The metric unit of mass equal to one thousandth of a kilogram. One gram equals approximately 15.432 grains or 0.035 273 966 ounce.
A volume unit equal to one milliliter used as a denominator to build a derived unit expressed as a ratio. (NCI)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of medicinal substance(s) contained in a single item of a tablet dosage form comprising of compressed medicinal substance(s) with or without suitable diluents.

Concepts.definition: A dosing unit equal to the amount of active ingredient(s) contained in a tablet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The metric unit of mass concentration defined as the  concentration of one gram of a substance in unit volume of the mixture  equal to one cubic meter. The concept also refers to the metric unit of  mass density (volumic mass) defined as the density of substance which  mass equal to one gram occupies the volume one cubic meter.

Concepts.definition: A metric unit of mass concentration defined as the concentration of one gram of a substance per unit volume of the mixture equal to one cubic meter. The concept also refers to the metric unit of mass density (volumic mass) defined as the density of a substance which mass equal to one gram occupies the volume of one cubic meter.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: The distinguishing qualities or prominent aspect of a person, object, action, process, or substance.

RepresentationTerm.preferredName: Potency Unit Unified Code for Units of Measure Code
RepresentationTerm.preferredDefinition: The basic quantity or increment used to describe the strength of a product or amount of product in a package.:A code system intended to include all units of measures being contemporarily used in international science,:A system of numbered categories for representation of data.

Concepts.definition: The basic quantity or increment used to describe the strength of a product or amount of product in a package.

Concepts.longName: Unified Code for Units of Measure
Concepts.definition: A code system intended to include all units of measures being contemporarily used in international science, engineering, and business. Its purpose is to facilitate unambiguous electronic communication of quantities together with their units.
A symbol or combination of symbols which is assigned to the members of a collection.
